# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: great-yarmouth
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:great-yarmouth/1926-in-the-united-kingdom] Events from the year **1926 in the United Kingdom**.
[src:great-yarmouth/1926-in-the-united-kingdom] The year was dominated by the general strike.
[src:great-yarmouth/1928-in-the-united-kingdom] Events from the year **1928 in the United Kingdom**.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] A census of the population of the United Kingdom is taken every ten years.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The **2011 census** was held in all countries of the UK on 27 March 2011.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] It was the first UK census which could be completed online via the Internet.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics (ONS) is responsible for the census in England and Wales, the General Register Office for Scotland (GROS) is responsible for the census in Scotland, and the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA) is responsible for the census in Northern Ireland.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics is the executive office of the UK Statistics Authority, a non-ministerial department formed in 2008 and which reports directly to Parliament.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] ONS is the UK Government's single largest statistical producer of independent statistics on the UK's economy and society, used to assist the planning and allocation of resources, policy-making and decision-making.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] ONS designs, manages and runs the census in England and Wales.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In its capacity as the national statistics office for the United Kingdom, ONS also compiles and releases census tables for the United Kingdom when the data from England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland are complete.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In the run-up to the census both the main UK political parties expressed concerns about the increasing cost and the value for money of the census, and it was suggested that the 2011 census might be the last decennial census to be taken.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first results from the 2011 census, age and sex, and occupied households estimates for England and Wales and Northern Ireland, were released on 16 July 2012.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first results for Scotland, and the first UK-wide results, were published on 17 December 2012.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] More detailed and specialised data were published from 2013.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Registrar General John Rickman conducted the first census of Great Britain's population, and was responsible for the ten-yearly reports published between 1801 and 1831.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] During the first 100 years of census-taking the population of England and Wales grew more than threefold, to around 32 million, and that of Scotland, where a separate census has been carried out since 1861, to about 4.5 million.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] From 1911 onwards rapid social change, scientific breakthroughs, and major world events affected the structure of the population.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] A fire that destroyed census records in 1931, and the declaration of war in 1939, made the 1951 census hugely significant in recording 30 years of change over one of the most turbulent periods in British history.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 1971 census was run by the newly created Office of Population Censuses and Surveys (OPCS), a body formed by the merger of the General Register Office and Government Social Survey.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 1996 the Office for National Statistics (ONS) was formed by merging the Central Statistical Office (CSO), OPCS and the statistics division of the Department of Employment; the first census it ran was in 2001.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2008 the UK Statistics Authority was established as an independent body.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] A population census is a key instrument for assessing the needs of local communities.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] When related to other data sources such as housing or agricultural censuses, or sample surveys, the data becomes even more useful.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Most countries of the world take censuses: the United Nations recommends that countries take a census at least once every ten years.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Twenty-one out of 40 countries in Europe are engaged in the 2010–2011 census round The design for the 2011 census reflected changes in society since 2001 and asked questions to help paint a detailed demographic picture of England and Wales, as it stood on census day, 27 March 2011.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Data collected by the census is used to provide statistical outputs which central government uses to plan and allocate local authority services funding, and which local authorities themselves use to identify and meet the needs of their local communities.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Other organisations that use census data include healthcare organisations, community groups, researchers and businesses.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The questionnaires, including people's personal information, are kept confidential for 100 years before being released to the public, providing an important source of information for historical, demographic and genealogy research.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for England and Wales included around 25 million households.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] People could complete and submit their questionnaire online, or fill it in on paper and post it back in a pre-addressed envelope.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Guidance was provided online and through the census helpline.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Completed questionnaires were electronically tracked and field staff followed up with households that did not return a questionnaire.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In these cases field staff delivered and collected questionnaires and, where needed, provided advice or assistance in completing the questionnaire.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] There was a legal requirement to complete the 2011 census questionnaire, under the terms of the Census Act 1920.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] As at 27 March 2011 everyone who had lived or intended to live in the country for three months or more was required to complete a questionnaire.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Failure to return a completed questionnaire could lead to a fine and criminal record.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Lockheed Martin UK, the UK arm of US-based aerospace, defence, security, and technology company Lockheed Martin was awarded the contract to provide services for the census comprising questionnaire printing, a customer contact centre and data capture and processing.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The contract was valued at £150 million, approximately one third of the total £482 million census budget.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Concerns were raised during contract negotiations that the US PATRIOT Act could be used to force Lockheed Martin to reveal census data to US authorities.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Several groups called for a boycott of the census over the involvement of Lockheed Martin, including the Stop the War Coalition, and the Christian thinktank Ekklesia.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The groups were concerned about sharing data with a company involved in surveillance and data processing for the CIA and FBI; and also providing funding to an arms company making nuclear missiles and cluster bombs.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Green Party also objected, and campaigned unsuccessfully to stop Lockheed Martin getting the contract, although no decision was made about whether or not to call for a boycott.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Census Alert campaign group also decided against calling for a boycott.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Liberal Conspiracy said a boycott would be counter-productive, as the census is used to distribute funding to local services.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Liberal Conspiracy reports that a council may lose £22,000 over 10 years for each person who does not complete the census.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The census for England and Wales was trialled in 135,000 households in Lancaster, the London Borough of Newham and Anglesey on 11 October 2009.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] A test was also carried out in Birmingham at the same time.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The questions for the 2011 census were the same as those trialled in the 2009 Census Rehearsal.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Order for the 2011 Census (including the proposed question topics, census date and who should complete the questionnaire) was laid before Parliament in October 2009 and was approved by Parliament and became law in December 2009.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Capita Group was contracted by ONS to recruit, train and administer the pay for the 35,000 temporary ONS workers who worked as field staff for the 2011 census.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The total cost of the 2011 census in England and Wales over the period from 2004/05 to 2015/16 is estimated to be £482 million.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] This is more than twice the £210m spent on the 2001 census.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] This breaks down to a cost of 87 pence per person, per year (over the life of the census – ten years).
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] "The cost equates to about 87p a year per person, demonstrating excellent value for money.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The per capita costs in the UK are less than for many other European countries that carry out similar censuses.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In summary, this census will meet crucial requirements for statistical information that Government and others cannot do without." Minister of State, Cabinet Office (Angela E.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Both the main UK political parties had expressed concerns about the rising costs and value of a ten-yearly census, and on coming into office the UK coalition government had gone as far as suggesting that the 2011 census might be the last of its kind.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In July 2010 the UK government asked ONS to explore other methods of measuring the population.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2011 the three national statistics bodies, ONS, GROS and NISRA set up a co-ordinated research project known as Beyond 2011.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The project reported its findings in March 2014 and recommended that a UK-wide census in 2021 should take place, and that better use should be made of other demographic data sources.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The general style of the questionnaire was similar to that of the 2001 census.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] A rehearsal questionnaire was released in 2009.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Several new identity and status options were included for the first time.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2001 only 38 people were reported to have been prosecuted for refusing to complete a questionnaire.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2011 those who refused to complete the census questionnaire or included false information could face a fine of up to £1,000.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] A team of compliance staff were recruited to follow up by visiting those householders who refused to complete a questionnaire or where their questionnaire was not returned or completed correctly.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Advertising promoted the notion of how the UK 2011 census would help to shape Britain's future in areas such as healthcare and education.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] TV adverts, for example, depicted Origami, in census colours, forming objects including school computers and buses.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] A short sentence under the census logo informed the viewer that the census was a duty that must be undertaken.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] From 7 April 2011 advertising focused on reminding people to complete and return by post or submit online.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] A question about the number of bedrooms a household has, as well as the names, gender and birth dates of any overnight guests was criticised as "bedroom snooping" by the Conservative Party in opposition.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Although some 37,000 people recorded their identity as Cornish by manually writing it on the form in the 2001 census, no tick-box was provided in 2011 to select Cornish as a White British national identity, despite campaigns.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] As a consequence, posters were created by the census organisation and Cornwall Council which advised residents of how they could identify themselves as Cornish by writing it in the ethnicity, national identity and main language sections.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally, people could record Cornwall as their country of birth.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] During the consultation on the 2011 census the British Humanist Association raised several concerns about question 20, "What is your religion?".
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The BHA argued it was a leading question, and suggested that it should be phrased as two questions, "Do you have a religion?" and "If so, what is it?".
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] It contended that by placing the religion question near the ethnicity question it would encourage some responders to associate religion with cultural identity.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The BHA also ran adverts during March 2011 encouraging the use of the 'no religion' box in the questionnaire.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for Northern Ireland had 59 questions in total.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] 14 were about the household and its accommodation and 45 questions were for each individual member of the household to complete.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The rehearsal was held on Sunday 11 October 2009 in two areas, Derriaghy and Moy & Benburb, covering approximately 5,000 households.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for Northern Ireland costing around £21.8 million over the six-year period 2008–2014.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Over the ten-year cycle the cost is expected to be about £25 million.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In Scotland, a wholly owned subsidiary of information technology company CACI was contracted to gather information.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] CACI "provided interrogators who worked at Abu Ghraib prison at the height of the prisoner abuse scandal".
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 Scotland census asked 13 household questions and up to 35 questions for each individual.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Plans were rehearsed in west Edinburgh and Lewis and Harris.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census was the first to include a question asking about the ability to read, write and understand the Scots language alongside the question for ability in Scottish Gaelic and English languages.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Responsibility for the release of data from the 2011 census is split between the Office for National Statistics (ONS) for England and Wales, the General Register Office for Scotland (GROS) for Scotland and the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA).
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The ONS announced in March the release plan for the results of the 2011 census which stated in July 2012.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] NISRA made a similar announcement with identical release plan.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In June 2012 GROS advised on its release plan which commences in December 2012.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The releases will comprise data sets enabling the standard comparison with previous census data reports as well as over a hundred new data sets based on the new questions asked in the 2011 census.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] NISRA, ONS and GROS each publish a schedule stating what documents they will release and when.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Those documents are called a "prospectus".
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Each prospectus is not fixed, but changes as schedules are changed or documents are late.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The prospectuses are linked to in the table below.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics is responsible for publishing United Kingdom wide 2011 census data.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] These are co-ordinated releases coinciding with data published by the three national statistical authorities.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population data including data for males and females for the United Kingdom and revised estimates England, Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population numbers (rounded), by five-year age bands, sex and densities and household sata at national and local authority level.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates (unrounded) by single year of age and sex for the UK and all local authorities (or equivalent) in the UK, along with UK historic population pyramids (1951–2011).
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 1 – Census Profiles; Population, People and Places, Health and Social Care, Travel and Transport.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] National and Local Authority geographies.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 2 – Census Profiles; Qualifications and Labour Market.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 3 – Multivariate, Local and Detailed Characteristics tables for: Living arrangements; Household composition; and Accommodation type.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] A series of further releases, subsequent to the four main releases of 2011 Census statistics including migration tables, workplace tables, detailed religion and ethnic group tables, and statistics relating to alternative population bases.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Specialist products would include:- Small population groups; microdata; flow data (also known as origin-destination statistics).
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] It is also suggested that data organised around alternative population bases may be produced.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The original plans of the ONS, covering England and Wales, confirmed that there would be four stages of data release starting in July 2012 and running until October 2013.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] This was increased to five stages in October 2013.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] A detailed commentary accompanies each release along with relevant reference materials.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally there will be graphic visualisations providing further clarification and comparison between different data sets and comparison over time using data from earlier censuses.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] There will also be more specialist reports and products.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Certain data bases will also be produced in the Welsh language.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick univariate (single parameter) statistics based on output levels, with release based on geography.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] (e.g. local authority, wards and parish/ community) tabulated by population count and percentages and accessible by post code.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key Statistics for local authorities in England and Wales comprising data which adds detail to the population estimates published in July 2012.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] It includes population information on international migration, age, ethnicity, national identity, health, housing and religion.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] For Wales, there is data on the Welsh language and population data on unitary authorities.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Statistical tables for Output Areas (OAs) and for wards.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Background information covering families, general health and disability, unpaid care, language, occupation and industry, qualifications and economic activity.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics for postcode sectors, health areas and Welsh Government devolved constituencies, and the key statistics for national parks in England and Wales, with a separate release for Wales only.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Statistical tables for non-UK short-term residents in England and Wales and quick statistics for England and Wales on national identity, passports held and country of birth, with a separate release for Wales only.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] More detailed cross tabulation of data topics: Migration; ethnicity, identity, language and religion; health; and Welsh tables.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed Characteristics tables for the themes of demography and families at local authority, MSOA and ward level.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] English language proficiency for regions, local authorities, 2011 Census Merged Wards and MSOAs in England and Wales.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first Local Characteristics tables for the topics of ethnicity, identity, language and religion for Output Areas, unitary and local authorities and regions.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristics tables for the topics of health and unpaid care for Output Areas.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Follow up to Release 3.2b on 12 July 2013.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristic Tables for the topic of migration for Output Areas.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristics on travel to work and car and van availability for Output Areas.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In addition to the six main releases phases further supplementary, smaller scale and specialist releases including; Small population groups, Microdata (teaching files, safeguarded files and secure files), Origin-destination data, and Alternate population bases.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release plans for Northern Ireland were set out by the NISRA.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release phases are closely synchronised with those of the ONS for England and Wales with some marginal variations to allow for local administrative arrangements.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Usual resident population by single age and sex.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Usual resident population by single age and sex for Local Government Districts, etc.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Household number and size by geographic units.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key statistics for NI and Local Government Districts etc.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Quick statistics for all geographies and population and household estimates for lower geographies.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed characteristics for NI-wide and all local authority and other geographies (including religion, identity and health).
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed characteristics for NI (including ethnicity, country of birth and language).
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Remaining detailed characteristics for NI including labour market and housing.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] All outstanding detailed characteristics for the remaining geographic areas.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Multivariate local characteristic tables and detailed themes around: economic activity; country of birth; occupation; and unpaid care.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release plans for Scotland were set out by the GROS Release phase dates are partly in sync with those of the other UK constituent country statistical authorities, however the first release was scheduled for six months after the first releases by the other authorities.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Consequently, release of UK-wide data has been scheduled so as to coincide with release plans for Scotland's Census releases.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates, based on resident households, communal establishments and age bands.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Estimates of the usually resident population of Scotland rounded to the nearest thousand, broken down by age and sex.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] An estimate of the total population in each council area, rounded to nearest thousand.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates by five-year age bands and sex for Scotland and each council area.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population and household changes since 2001 census.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population dependency ratios for Scotland and each council area.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] First release of unrounded population estimates and household communal establishment numbers, by single year of age and sex.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] (First published as rounded data in December 2012 and March 2013).
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics; Census Profiles; headcounts and geography products.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Comprising; Estimates by postcode and geography products.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] This release will represent the start of the dissemination of detailed census statistics for small areas.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for marriage and civil partnership, ethnicity, religion, language proficiency, country of birth and national identity, heath (excluding long-term health), age, arrival in UK, population and households, housing and accommodation, car and van ownership.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: Scotland, Council Areas and Health Boards.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for Education and Labour Market.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: All output areas and Data Zones.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Also the key and quick statistics for the remaining geographies of the topics covered in Release 2a.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for Living Arrangements and Travel to Work Methods.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: All levels of census geographies.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Multivariate statistics, comprising a combination of; age, sex, resident type, ethnic group, economic activity, general health and provision of unpaid care, country of birth, and occupation.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local and Detailed Characteristics tables for Qualifications, Employment and Economic Activity, Travel for Work and Study.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local and Detailed Characteristics tables including; Travel to Work, Household, Qualifications and Long-term Health, Social Status and Economic Activity.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The United Kingdom Statistics Authority is responsible for coordinating the release of census data by the devolved statistics authorities.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] It publishes UK-wide census data results via the Office for National Statistics (ONS) site.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The UK Data Service provides a central point of reference for all country-specific census data releases via its Learning Hub site.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Primary responsibility for country-specific 2011 census data rests with the statistical authorities for each of the UK's constituent countries.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Each authority has at least one dedicated central source from which data can be downloaded or ordered.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] For England and Wales the ONS provides the access to primary data via its 2011 census siteArchived 29 January 2016 at the UK Government Web Archive.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally, data organised by local authority or post code is available on the Neighbourhood Statistics Archived 20 October 2010 at the Wayback Machine site, and nomis, a source of detailed census results which can be assembled into bespoke data sets.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] For Scotland the General Registrar Office for Scotland (GROS) part of National Records of Scotland (NRS) to maintain access via its Scotlands Census site, and for Northern Ireland the Statistics and Research Authority (NISRA) uses the Northern Ireland Neighbourhood Information Service (NINIS).
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The format of all the pre-defined statistical tables is standardised as far as practical across the publishing authorities.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Since the 2001 UK census the naming conventions for the tables have been revised following research into the approaches adopted by other census publishing bodies around the world.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The statistical authorities are also making available bulk data in Comma-separated values (CSV) file format which can be downloaded from online data warehouse facilities.
[src:great-yarmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In addition to the standard releases and online bulk access the statistical authorities provide a commissioned data service whereby other data configurations can be purchased, under license, by customers and will subsequently be made freely available to other users.
[src:great-yarmouth/2019-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Events from the year **2019 in the United Kingdom**.
[src:great-yarmouth/2019-in-the-united-kingdom-p01] Lack of agreement on how to proceed with withdrawing from the EU led to substantial political turmoil during this year culminating in the 2019 General election in which the pro-Brexit Conservative party gained a significant majority of seats.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The **A12** is a major road in Eastern England.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] It runs north-east/south-west between London and the coastal town of Lowestoft in the north-eastern corner of Suffolk, following a similar route to the Great Eastern Main Line until Ipswich.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] A section of the road between Lowestoft and Great Yarmouth became part of the A47 in 2017.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] Between the junctions with the M25 and the A14, the A12 forms part of the unsigned Euroroute E30 (prior to 1985, it was the E8).
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] Unlike most A roads, this section of the A12, together with the A14 and the A55, has junction numbers as if it were a The 52 miles (84 km) section of the A12 through Essex has sections of dual two lanes and dual three lanes, with eight changes in width between the M25 to Ipswich.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] It was named as Britain's worst road because of "potholes and regular closures due to roadworks" in a 2007 survey by Cornhill Insurance.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The A12 is covered by the National Highways *A12 / A120 route based strategy*.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] Starting just north of the Blackwall Tunnel, where it connects end on to the A102, it heads north through Bow and Hackney Wick, then north-east through Leyton and Romford, then into Essex, passing Brentwood and Colchester.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] In Suffolk, it passes Ipswich and Saxmundham, then follows the coast through Lowestoft before entering Norfolk, passing through Gorleston-on-Sea and ending at Great Yarmouth.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] In February 2017, the route was renumbered between Great Yarmouth and Lowestoft to become the A47.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] In June 2024, most of the A1117 was renumbered as the A12, incorporating the Lowestoft Gull Wing Bridge, where the A12 now terminates at the A47 in North Lowestoft.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The A12 was formed in 1922 as part of the Great Britain road numbering scheme, and initially the route went from Stratford to Gallows Corner along the present A118 road before continuing to Great Yarmouth.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] This section in London was rerouted to run on Eastern Avenue by the mid-1940s, and extended to follow the current route from Blackwall Tunnel along the East Cross Route, (previously the A102(M) & A106), the M11 link road in 1999.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The route from London to Essex has long been important, with Old Ford being the location of an ancient Celtic crossing of the River Lea.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The route was altered slightly by the Romans who created a paved road from London to Colchester, which was part of *Inter V* on the Antonine Itinerary, and parts of this were used by a turnpike road, the Great Essex Road.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The crossing of the Lea moved to its current location at Bow around 1110 when Matilda, wife of Henry I, ordered a distinctively bow-shaped, three-arched bridge to be built over the river.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] A map from 1766 shows a route from London to Lowestoft which follows much of the current A12.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The "Ipswich to South Town and Bungay Turnpike Trust" was established in 1785, operating between Ipswich and Great Yarmouth.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The trust was wound up in 1872 following the arrival of the East Suffolk Line which was fully operational between the two towns in 1859.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] Following the demise of the Turnpike trust, responsibility reverted to parish councils until the new county councils took over in 1889.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] A new section of the A12, known as the "M11 link road" or "A12 Hackney-M11 Link Road", was built in the early 1990s in the face of the major M11 link road protest and finally opened in October 1999.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The section of road had originally been proposed in 1903 in a Royal Commission on London Traffic.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] A public inquiry had been held in September 1961 and a further three public inquiries, a Parliamentary Bill and a High Court challenge had been required before the work started.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] Initiated in 2000, the London to Ipswich Multi-modal study reported its conclusions late in 2002.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] In 2008 improvements were made to the junction between the A12 and the M25 to increase slip-road capacity, in particular for clockwise M25 traffic turning north onto the A12, and to ease congestion on the Brook Street Roundabout (serving the M25, A12 and local Brentwood traffic as the A1023).
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The bascule bridge in Lowestoft was built in 1972, and was refurbished in spring 2008.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] Essex County Council carried out its own inquiry into the road in 2008, with work on a £12.4m scheme for a new junction on the A12 at Cuckoo Farm, Colchester adjacent to the Colchester Community Stadium, subsequently starting in December 2009.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] It was promoted by Essex County Council who prepared plans in 2001 and was financed from the Community Infrastructure Fund.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The section of A12 between Brentwood and Ipswich is classed as a major trunk road, managed by Highways England.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The section between Ipswich and Lowestoft was de-trunked in 2001, with control passing to Suffolk County Council.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] This section is primarily single carriageway.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] In 2011, at Junction 33 (Copdock Interchange) the junction was widened and improved to ease the increasing traffic flow along the road.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] A widening of the section from Chelmsford to the A120 junction near Colchester is proposed with a start date in 2023/2024 and expected to complete around 2028.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] Much of the original route has been bypassed around historic town centres such as Brentwood and Witham.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] In larger settlements such as Chelmsford, Colchester and Ipswich the original route has been bypassed twice.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The Eastern Avenue was built in the 1920s as a bypass for the section between Romford and Ilford, meeting what was the A11 at Leytonstone.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] It was numbered A106 until the 1930s when it became part of the A12.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The 5-mile (8 km) long Brentwood bypass was opened in November 1965.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] A bypass for Chelmsford was first included in the roads programme in 1968.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] Draft orders for the southern bypass were published in 1974, however the public inquiry in 1975 suggested that the government should re-examine the appropriateness of a "central route" and the government delayed the road.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] In 1979 the government announced that it would proceed with the southern dual two lane route which opened in 1986.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The Wickham Market bypass opened in July 1976, providing a much needed improvement to avoid the narrow, one-lane wide section of road through Wickham Market.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] Ipswich's "Southern by-pass" via the Orwell Bridge was opened in 1982.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] This section, when first numbered, was part of the A45 and later designated as part of the A14.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The Martlesham bypass (previously known as the Kesgrave and Martlesham Bypass) was completed in 1987/1988 as was the Saxmundham bypass.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] A white paper, *Roads for Prosperity*, published in 1989, proposed to widen the Chelmsford Bypass and the section from Hatfield Peverel to Witham to dual 3 lane; it also proposed widening the section from Saxmundham to Lowestoft and from Wickham Market to Farnham to dual 2 lanes.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] It also included a 'new route from the M25 to Chelmsford' as a dual two lane road following the proposed route of the M12 motorway.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] Mary, Martlesham to Wickham Market, Wickham Market to Saxmundham, the bypass around Saxmundham, Saxmundham to south of Wrentham, South of Wrentham to Kessingland and the Lowestoft relief road.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] A public inquiry in the "Saxmundham to Wickham Market bypass" was held in 1995 but this road has not been built.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] Between 1968 and 2024 Lowestoft has seen various new roads built to bypass and divert the A12 away from the historic residential streets along the coastline.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] In the 60s/70s Bloodmoor Roundabout / Bloodmoor Road was completed, paving the way for the new route of the A12 from the south.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] 1990 saw the construction of Peto Way, followed by Millennium Way in 1998 (the "Northern Relief Road") (formerly part of the A1117), however it wouldn't be until 2024 these were incorporated into the A12.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] In 2006, the 1.5 mile Tom Crisp Way "Southern Relief Road" opened, diverting the A12 away from the cliffs and built up Kirkely.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] 2015 saw Millennium Way extended to connect to the A47 at Corton and 2024 saw a new third river crossing built, the Gull Wing Bridge, which linked the northern and southern relief roads and completes the A12 bypass in Lowestoft.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The entire bypass consists of single carriageway roads with modern cycle and pedestrian facilities and a mostly 40 MPH speed limit.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] During the 1940s, there were plans for a motorway between South Woodford and Brentwood, initially dubbed Radial Route 7, which later became the M12 motorway in the 1960s.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] This would have run from the North Circular Road in London, at the base of the current M11 motorway, joining the A12 north of Brentwood.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The North Circular was to be upgraded to motorway-standard as part of Ringway 2 and be designated as the M15 motorway.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The M11 was to have provided a motorway standard road into central London past Ringway 1, terminating at the Angel in Islington.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The M12 motorway was never built, although the junction of the M11 with the North Circular was designed to accommodate it.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The scheme was revived in the late 1980s, and extended the northern section to the A12 near Chelmsford.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] Plans for the M12 motorway were withdrawn in March 1994, following a review of the trunk roads programme.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The A12 starts just north of the Blackwall Tunnel at a junction with the A102 and the A13.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] From here to past Ipswich (including the entire section through London) the road is a dual carriageway.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] North of the junction, the A12 heads northwards as a 2/3 lane dual carriageway mostly at street level.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] This stretch of road is known as the Blackwall Tunnel Northern Approach.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] This stretch ends at the triple-layer interchange with the A11 at Bow Road where it becomes the East Cross Route.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] This is mainly a 3/4 lane dual carriageway built mainly on flyovers and underpasses and was built in the late 1960s, previously called the A102(M).
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The road turns North Eastwards at the unfinished Hackney Wick Interchange where the carriageways split and the northbound carriageway has a right hand entrance.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] When the London Ringways plan was being proposed, a motorway (North Cross Route) was to end here and the M11 was meant to extend from its current terminus on the A406 through this junction and to Angel.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The section from the Lea Interchange to Leytonstone, also known as the M11 Link road, was built in the 1990s in the face of a major road protest.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] During this work the old section as far as Wanstead was rebuilt as a dual carriageway.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] Prior to that, the A12 started at the Green Man Roundabout at Leytonstone, and was single carriageway west of Wanstead Underground station.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] It now has an underpass at that roundabout, which again is a junction with the old A11.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] East of Wanstead, the A12 runs roughly due east.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] It is known as Eastern Avenue, then Eastern Avenue West and Eastern Avenue East, built in the 1920s as a bypass for the section of the Roman road from Colchester to London running through Ilford and Romford (today's A118).
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The eastern end of the Eastern Avenue is Gallows Corner in the London Borough of Havering, just east of Romford.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The junction also marks the start-point of the A127 Southend Arterial Road, also 1920s vintage.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] At the roundabout, an extemporised two-lane flyover still provides priority for A12 eastbound to A127 traffic (and vice versa).
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] However, the A12 now veers roughly north-eastward, because it starts to follow the course of the Roman road; the Romans started building this road from Colchester, their original capital for the province.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] However, the 2.5-mile (4.0 km) stretch from Gallows Corner to the junction with the M25 motorway, called Colchester Road, is still perfectly straight.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The M25 junction is number 28; it also marks where the A12 crosses the boundary from London to Essex.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] Originally, the A12 followed the route of the Roman road closely and so was fairly straight, but there are now several town bypasses, so the road through Essex now has several meanders.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] It is this stretch of the A12, particularly between Chelmsford and Colchester, which has led to the poor reputation for surface quality of the A12.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] This is mainly for its bumpy or potholed surface, mostly due to worn concrete surfaces.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] In an ongoing process these sections are being relaid with tarmac, however some sections including the Kelvedon bypass, and between Copford and Stanway have yet to be resurfaced.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] Built in 1982, the A12 Colchester bypass provides an uninterrupted dual carriageway where the national speed limit of 70 mph applies.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] Before 1982, the A12 took a route much closer to Colchester itself, and although still a bypass it consisted of urban single carriageways with roundabouts and pedestrian crossings.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The old bypass is still in existence – the western half now forms part of the A1124 and the eastern half part of the A133.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The Suffolk stretch of the A12 starts with the Capel St Mary bypass.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] Originally the route from the Northern end of this bypass ran through the villages of Washbrook and Copdock and into Ipswich.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] When Ipswich's Southern by-pass was built in the early 1980s, the route picked up from the northern Capel St Mary junction (now numbered 32b), to pass to the West of the original line – this allowed the relevant ground works and interchanges to be completed with minimal traffic disruption.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The old dual carriageway through Washbrook and Copdock is blocked off at White's Corner and was renumbered to be the C475.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] A footpath still exists which enables passage underneath the A14.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The old route through Ipswich was renumbered as the A1214 following construction of the Ipswich Southern By-pass.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The old route is more locally known by the road names, notably "London Road" to the Town Centre and Woodbridge Road out the other side.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The Ipswich Southern By-pass allows the A12 to overlap the A14 to Seven Hills Interchange, 7 miles (11 km) from the Copdock junction, where the A12 reappears and heads North.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] As the A14 the road passes over the large Orwell Bridge with total length of 1,287 metres.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] This has a summit at 43 metres above the river giving a humped feel with reduced visibility for traffic.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] There are at-grade roundabout junctions past BT Adastral Park at Martlesham and around the Woodbridge bypass.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] For most of its remaining length through Suffolk the A12 is a mostly single carriageway road, and in many places its speed limit is less than the national limit, for example as it passes through towns and villages.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] During 2003/2004 some of these speed restrictions were further reduced from 40 mph (64 km/h) to 30 mph (48 km/h).
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] There are, though, a few stretches of dual carriageway between the Woodbridge bypass and Lowestoft (at Wickham Market, Saxmundham, Wangford and Kessingland).
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] This section of the A12 was detrunked in 2001 as part of the Highways Agency's streamlining of its Trunk Road Network.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] Control was therefore passed to the local authorities.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] Just south of Blythburgh, the old milestone shows it is 100 miles (160 km) to London.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The A12 ran through Lowestoft for about 5 miles (8 km) on urban 30 mph (48 km/h) limited roads.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] However, as of June 2006, the A12 now follows the course of the new single carriageway 40 miles per hour (64 km/h) Southern Relief Road that joins the A47 at Lowestoft Bascule Bridge.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] In June 2024, a small segment of the B1531 was renumbered the A12 and upgraded with a new roundabout junction and 50m of dual carriageway.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The A12 is now carried over the river by a new third river crossing, the Gull Wing Bridge, where it meets the former A1117 which was renumbered as the A12.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] This carries the A12 via the towns Northern Relief Roads to the A47 near to Corton, where the A12 terminates.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] A bypass for various villages was proposed in 1986 as part of the government's 1989 Roads for Prosperity white paper which detailed many road schemes across the country.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] Suffolk county council considered a bypass for the villages of Farnham, Stratford St Andrew, Glemham and Marlesford for the 2006 Local Transport Plan.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The scheme will not be implemented until after 2016.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] Essex county council has put forwards plans for a bypass of Chelmsford connecting Junction 19 of the A12 to the A131.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] Plans to upgrade additional sections of the A120 into a dual two-lane carriageway were scrapped in 2009.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] In response to this increasing congestion, Essex County Council announced it would hold an A12 inquiry which was tasked with deciding how to improve the A12 and prevent the congestion.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The inquiry was headed by Sir David Rowlands, KCB, a former Permanent Secretary at the Department for Transport, with professor Stephen Glaister, David Quarmby and Lord Whitty, all with significant knowledge of the transport sector.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] The inquiry began taking submissions in April 2008.
[src:great-yarmouth/a12-road-england] Comments were also received from over two hundred members of the public and through a petition organised by the Essex Chronicle newspaper.
[src:great-yarmouth/a143-road] The **A143** is a road that runs from the Gorleston-on-Sea area of Great Yarmouth, in Norfolk to Haverhill in Suffolk.
[src:great-yarmouth/a143-road] For much of the route (between Gorleston-on-Sea and Bury St Edmunds) the road is classified as a primary route.
[src:great-yarmouth/a143-road] Over the years the road has been much improved with new by-passes opening at regular intervals.
[src:great-yarmouth/a143-road] The last of these being the Broome – Ellingham bypass in March 2002.
[src:great-yarmouth/a143-road] The A143 begins on Beccles Road as an off slip from the A47 road, in the Gorleston-on-Sea area of Great Yarmouth, this is close to the Stone Cross Roundabout.
[src:great-yarmouth/a143-road] The road continues in a south-westerly direction.
[src:great-yarmouth/a143-road] On leaving Gorleston-on-Sea there is a very short section of dual carriageway and from there the road is a strictly rural affair and there are not many straight sections.
[src:great-yarmouth/a143-road] This part of the route runs through some lovely countryside and passes many local attractions along the way.
[src:great-yarmouth/a143-road] These include Fritton Lake, Caldecotte Hall and Redwings horse sanctuary.
[src:great-yarmouth/a143-road] The route passes through the villages of St Olaves and Haddiscoe before joining up, for about 1 mile, with the A146 at a roundabout a few miles from Beccles.
[src:great-yarmouth/a143-road] During the summer months this is an area very popular with holiday makers so the road can be quite busy at times.
[src:great-yarmouth/a143-road] The road in this area has undergone major changes in the last few decades.
[src:great-yarmouth/a143-road] The original route took you through the centre of many towns and villages and has now been renumbered the B1062.
[src:great-yarmouth/a143-road] From the Suffolk town of Bungay until Harleston the road follows the route of the now defunct Waveney Valley Line railway and progress along this section of the road is generally quite good as there are no reduced speed limits, save for Billingford.
[src:great-yarmouth/a143-road] The road eventually intersects with the A140 Norwich to Ipswich road, just outside the Norfolk town of Diss.
[src:great-yarmouth/a143-road] Once the road leaves Diss it returns to an older route.
[src:great-yarmouth/a143-road] This takes it through a number of villages on the way to Bury including Great Barton, where there has long been a campaign for a bypass.
[src:great-yarmouth/a143-road] Along this section the road crosses the A1088 Thetford to Woolpit road at Ixworth.
[src:great-yarmouth/a143-road] On arrival in Bury the road travels underneath the A14 and at this point the route is no longer considered primary and now becomes an ordinary A road.
[src:great-yarmouth/a143-road] It then continues to wind through some nice Suffolk countryside until it links up with the A1307 at Haverhill.
[src:great-yarmouth/a143-road] From here it is only a short distance to the M11 which gives easy access southwards to London and north to Cambridge.
[src:great-yarmouth/a143-road] There is a section that won't allow overtaking on the left until Wickhambrook but then it won't last long.
[src:great-yarmouth/a143-road] There is another section that follows a similar pattern but due to multiple painted islands.
[src:great-yarmouth/a143-road] The road has been criticised for its road safety record, especially in Suffolk, where the road has been described as consistently one of the most dangerous roads in the county.
[src:great-yarmouth/a143-road] Along the route of the A143 you pass next to or very near to a number of railway stations.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Yarmouth has been a resort since 1760 and a gateway from the Norfolk Broads to the North Sea.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Holidaymaking rose when a railway opened in 1844, bringing easier, cheaper access and some new settlements.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Wellington Pier opened in 1854, and Britannia Pier in 1858.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Through the 20th century, Yarmouth boomed as a resort, with a promenade, pubs, trams, fish-and-chip shops, theatres, the Pleasure Beach, the Sea Life Centre, the Hippodrome Circus, the Time and Tide Museum and a Victorian seaside Winter Garden in cast iron and glass.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Great Yarmouth is located on a 3.1-mile (5.0 km) spit of land between the North Sea and River Yare.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] It features historic rows of houses in narrow streets and a main tourist sector on the seafront.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] It is linked to Gorleston, Cobholm and Southtown by Haven Bridge and to the A47 and A149 by Breydon Bridge.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The urban area covers 8.3 sq mi (21 km2) and according to the Office for National Statistics (ONS) in 2002 had a population of 47,288.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] It is the main town in the Borough of Great Yarmouth.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The ONS identifies a Great Yarmouth urban area as having a population of 68,317, which includes the sub-areas of Caister-on-Sea (population 8,756) and Great Yarmouth (population 58,032).
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The wider Great Yarmouth borough had a population of around 92,500, which increased to 97,277 at the 2011 United Kingdom census.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Ethnically, Great Yarmouth was 92.8 per cent White British, with the next biggest ethnic demographic being Other White at 3.5 per cent – Eastern Europeans in the main.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Great Yarmouth (Gernemwa, Yernemuth) lies near the site of the Roman fort camp of Gariannonum at the mouth of the River Yare.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Its situation having attracted fishermen from the Cinque Ports, a permanent settlement was made, and the town numbered 70 burgesses before the Norman Conquest.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Henry I placed it under the rule of a reeve.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] In 1101, the Church of St Nicholas was founded by Herbert de Losinga, the first Bishop of Norwich, and consecrated in 1119.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] This was to be the first of several priories founded in what was a wealthy trading centre of considerable importance.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] In 1208, King John granted a charter to Great Yarmouth.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The charter gave his burgesses of Yarmouth general liberties according to the customs of Oxford, a gild merchant and weekly hustings, amplified by several later charters asserting the rights of the borough against Little Yarmouth and Gorleston.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The town is bound to send to the sheriffs of Norwich every year "one hundred herrings, baked in twenty-four pasties", which the sheriffs are to deliver to the lord of the manor of East Carlton, who is then to convey them to the King.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] A hospital was founded in Great Yarmouth during the reign of Edward I by Thomas Fastolfe, father of Thomas Fastolf, Bishop of St David's.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] In 1551, a grammar school was founded, and the great hall of the old hospital was appropriated for its use.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The school was closed from 1757 to 1860 but re-established by charity trustees and settled in new buildings in 1872.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] In 1552, Edward VI granted a charter of admiralty jurisdiction, later confirmed and extended by James I.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Elizabeth I came to Great Yarmouth in July 1578.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] In 1668 a charter from Charles II extended the borough boundaries to also include Little Yarmouth (also known as Southtown), which lay on the opposite bank of the Yare in the parish of Gorleston in Suffolk.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] In 1703 a new charter from Queen Anne replaced the two bailiffs by a mayor.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] In 1673, during the Third Anglo-Dutch War, the Zealand Expedition was assembled in the town.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] In 1702, the Fishermen's Hospital was founded.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] In 1797, during the French Revolutionary Wars, the town was the main supply base for the North Sea Fleet.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The fleet collected at the Yarmouth Roads, from whence it sailed to the decisive Battle of Camperdown against the Dutch fleet.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] In 1803, Captain George Manby was appointed barrack-master at Great Yarmouth; during his time in post he invented the Manby mortar.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Again in 1807, during the Napoleonic Wars, the collected fleet sailed from the roadstead to the Battle of Copenhagen.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] From 1808 to 1814, the Admiralty in London could communicate with its ships in Yarmouth by a shutter telegraph chain.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Ships were routinely anchored offshore during the Napoleonic Wars and the town served as a supply base for the Royal Navy.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Part of an Ordnance Yard survives from this period on Southtown Road, probably designed by James Wyatt: a pair of roadside lodges (which originally housed senior officers) frame the entrance to the site, which contains a sizeable armoury of 1806, a small barracks block and other ancillary buildings.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Originally the depot extended down to a wharf on the River Yare and was flanked by a pair of storehouses, but these and other buildings were destroyed in The Blitz.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] A grander survival is the former Royal Naval Hospital designed by William Pilkington, begun in 1806 and opened in 1811.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The hospital consisted of four two-storey pavilions set around a courtyard, with a colonnaded walkway linking them; each block contained eight wards.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] It served only briefly as a naval hospital, during the last years of the Napoleonic Wars, before being handed over to the Army for use as barracks.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] In the early 1860s, however, it reverted to medical use, being reopened as a naval psychiatric hospital.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] It continued to serve in this capacity until 1958, when the premises were transferred to the NHS.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] After its closure in 1993, the buildings were turned into private residences.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The town was the site of a bridge disaster and drowning tragedy on 2 May 1845, when the Yarmouth suspension bridge, crowded with children, collapsed under the weight, killing 79.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] They had gathered to watch a clown in a barrel being pulled by geese down the river.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] As he passed under the bridge, the weight shifted, causing the chains on the south side to snap, tipping over the bridge deck.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Great Yarmouth had an electric tramway system from 1902 to 1933.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] From the 1880s until the First World War, the town was a regular destination for Bass Excursions, when fifteen trains would take 8,000–9,000 employees of Bass's Burton brewery on an annual trip to the seaside.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] During World War I, Great Yarmouth was attacked by the Germans several times.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The first occasion was on 3 November 1914 when the town was subject to a brief bombardment.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The town experienced the first air raid on England, carried out by the German Imperial Navy's Zeppelin *L 3 (LZ 24)* on 19 January 1915.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Later that year, on 15 August, Ernest Martin Jehan became the first—and only—person to sink a steel submarine while commanding a sail-rigged Q-ship, off the coast of Great Yarmouth.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Although he led a crew, the feat is credited to him as the commanding officer.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The town was bombarded again by the German Navy on 24 April 1916.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] On the South Quay is a 17th-century Merchant's House, as well as Tudor, Georgian and Victorian buildings.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Behind South Quay is a maze of alleys and lanes known as "The Rows".
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Despite war damage, several have remained.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The town was badly affected by the North Sea flood of 1953.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] More recent flooding has also been a problem, with four floods in 2006, the worst being in September.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Torrential rain caused drains to block and an Anglian Water pumping station to break down, which caused flash flooding in which 90 properties were flooded up to 5 ft (1.5 m).
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] On 1 April 1974, the civil parish of Great Yarmouth was abolished.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The southern section of the 2 mi (3.2 km) A47 Great Yarmouth Western Bypass opened in May 1985, with the northern section opened in March 1986.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The bypass was re-numbered as part of the A12, until it returned to being part of the A47 in February 2017.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] In February 2023, there was an explosion on River Yare when disposal of unexploded ordnance from World War II resulted in accidental detonation.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The Tollhouse with dungeons, dating from the late 13th century, is one of Britain's oldest former gaols and oldest civic buildings.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Major sections of the medieval town walls survive around the parish cemetery and in parts of the old town.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Great Yarmouth Minster (the Minster Church of St Nicholas, founded in the 12th century as an act of penance) stands in Church Plain, just off the market place.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] It is the third largest parish church in England, after Beverley Minster in the East Riding of Yorkshire and Christchurch Priory in Dorset.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Neighbouring Church Plain has the 17th-century timber-framed house where Anna Sewell (1820–1878), author of *Black Beauty*, was born.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The market place, one of England's largest, has functioned since the 13th century.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] It is also home to the town's shopping sector and the famous Yarmouth chip stalls.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The smaller area south of the market is used as a performance area for community events and for access to the town's shopping centre, Market Gates.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Great Yarmouth railway station is the terminus of the Wherry Lines from Norwich.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Before the Beeching Axe, the town had several stations and a direct link to London down the east coast.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The only remaining signs of these are a coach park, where Beach Station once was, and the A12 relief road, which follows the route of the railway down into the embankment from Breydon Bridge.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Yarmouth has two piers: Britannia Pier (Grade II listed)) and Wellington Pier.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The theatre building on the latter was demolished in 2005 and reopened in 2008 as a family entertainment centre, including a ten-pin bowling alley overlooking the beach.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Britannia Pier holds the Britannia Theatre, which during the summer has featured acts such as Jim Davidson, Jethro, Basil Brush, Cannon and Ball, Chubby Brown, the Chuckle Brothers, and The Searchers.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] It is one of the few end-of-the-pier theatres surviving in England.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The Scroby Sands Wind Farm of thirty generators is within sight of the seafront, with its giant wind generators.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Also visible are grey seals during their breeding season.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The country's only full-time circus, Hippodrome Circus, is just off the seafront.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The Grade II listed Winter Gardens building sits next to the Wellington Pier.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The cast iron, framed glass structure was shipped by barge from Torquay in 1903, ostensibly without the loss of a single pane of glass.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Over the years, it has been used as a ballroom, roller skating rink and beer garden.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] In the 1990s, it was converted into a nightclub by Jim Davidson and has since been used as a family leisure venue.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] In the meantime, it has been named by the Victorian Society as a heritage building at risk of disrepair.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Great Yarmouth's seafront, known as "The Golden Mile", attracts millions of visitors each year to its sandy beaches, indoor and outdoor attractions and amusement arcades.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Great Yarmouth's Marine Parade has twelve Amusement Arcades within 2 square miles (5.2 km2), including: Atlantis, The Flamingo, Circus Circus, The Golden Nugget, The Mint, Leisureland, The Majestic, The Silver Slipper, The Showboat, Magic City, Quicksilver and The Gold Rush, opened in 2007.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] In addition to the two piers, tourist attractions on Marine Parade include Joyland, Pirates Cove Adventure Golf, Castaway Island Adventure Golf, the Marina Centre, the Sea Life Centre, Merrivale Model Village and the Pleasure Beach and Gardens.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] In August 2019, the Venetian Waterways and gardens in Great Yarmouth were reopened following a major restoration project delivered by contractor Blakedown Landscapes.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Originally constructed between 1926 and 1928 as a work-creation scheme, the site features canals and formal gardens that had fallen into disrepair, with waterways silted up and infrastructure neglected.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Supported by a £1.7 million grant from the Heritage Lottery Fund and assistance from volunteers, the restoration involved replanting the flowerbeds with 20,000 plants and refurbishing the original 1920s café.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The café and boat hire facilities are now operated by a social enterprise.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The South Denes area is home to the Grade I listed Norfolk Naval Pillar, known locally as the Britannia Monument or Nelson's Monument.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] This tribute to Nelson was completed in 1819, 24 years before the completion of Nelson's Column in London.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The monument, designed by William Wilkins, shows Britannia standing atop a globe holding an olive branch in her right hand and a trident in her left.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] There is a popular assumption in the town that the statue of Britannia was supposed to face out to sea but now faces inland due to a mistake during construction, although it is thought she is meant to face Nelson's birthplace at Burnham Thorpe.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The monument was originally planned to mark Nelson's victory at the Battle of the Nile, but fundraising was not completed until after his death, and it was instead dedicated to England's greatest naval hero.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] It is currently surrounded by an industrial estate, but there are plans to improve the area.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The Norfolk Nelson Museum on South Quay housed the Ben Burgess collection of Nelson memorabilia and was the only dedicated Nelson museum in England.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] It's several galleries that look at Nelson's life and personality, and at what life was like for men who sailed under him.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Charles Dickens used Yarmouth as a key location in his novel *David Copperfield*, and described the town as "the finest place in the universe".
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Dickens stayed at the Royal Hotel on the Marine Parade while writing the novel.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The Time and Tide Museum in Blackfriars Road, managed by Norfolk Museums Service, was nominated in the UK Museums Awards in 2005.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] It was built as part of a regeneration of the south of the town in 2003.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Its location in an old herring smokery harks back to the town's status as a major fishing port.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Sections of the historic town wall stand opposite the museum, next to the Great Yarmouth Potteries, part of which is housed in another former smokehouse.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The town wall is among the most complete medieval town walls in the country, with 11 of the 18 original turrets still standing.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Other museums in the town include the National Trust's Elizabethan House, the Great Yarmouth Row Houses, managed by English Heritage, and the privately owned Blitz and Pieces, based on the Home front during World War II.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The Maritime Heritage East partnership, based at the award-winning Time and Tide Museum, aims to raise the profile of maritime heritage and museum collections.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] In October 2021, street artist Banksy created several murals in the town as part of his set A Great British Spraycation.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] There are two tiers of local government covering Great Yarmouth, at district and county level: Great Yarmouth Borough Council and Norfolk County Council, based in Norwich.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The borough council meets at Great Yarmouth Town Hall in Hall Plain, which is a Grade II* listed building.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The original borough was entirely on the north side of the Yare, which formed the historic boundary between Norfolk and Suffolk.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] After the borough was enlarged to include Southtown in 1668, the borough straddled the two counties.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The borough was reformed to become a municipal borough in 1836 under the Municipal Corporations Act 1835, at which point the boundaries were enlarged to include all of the parish of Gorleston.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] When elected county councils were created in 1889, Great Yarmouth was considered large enough to provide its own county-level services and so it became a county borough, independent from Norfolk County Council.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] For ceremonial and judicial purposes, the borough continued to straddle Norfolk and Suffolk until 1 April 1891, when the county boundary was adjusted to place the whole borough in Norfolk.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The County Borough of Great Yarmouth was abolished in 1974 under the Local Government Act 1972.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The area became part of the larger Borough of Great Yarmouth, a lower-tier non-metropolitan district, with Norfolk County Council providing county-level services to the town for the first time.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] No successor parish was created for the area of the former county borough, which therefore became an unparished area, directly administered by Great Yarmouth Borough Council.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Great Yarmouth is a constituency represented in the House of Commons of the Parliament of the United Kingdom.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Its current MP, starting 5 July 2024, is Rupert Lowe, elected for Reform UK before he left the party and established Restore Britain.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The Yarmouth area provides habitats for some rare and unusual species.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The area between the piers is home to one of the largest roosts of Mediterranean gulls in the UK.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Breydon Water, just behind the town, is a major wader and waterfowl site, with winter roosts of over 100,000 birds.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Grey seal and common seal are frequently seen offshore, as are seabirds such as gannet, little auk, common scoter, razorbill, Gull and guillemot.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] This and the surrounding Halvergate Marshes are environmentally protected.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Most of the area is now managed by conservation organisations, principally the RSPB.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The North Denes area of the beach is an SSSI due to its dune plants, and supports many skylarks and meadow pipits, along with one of the largest little tern colonies in the UK each summer, and a small colony of grayling butterflies.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Other butterflies found include small copper and common blue.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The nearby cemetery is a renowned temporary roost for spring and autumn migrants.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Common redstart and pied flycatcher are often seen during their migration.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] It has also recorded the first sightings of some rare insects blown in from the continent.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The main local football club is Great Yarmouth Town, known as the Bloaters, which plays in the Eastern Counties League.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Its ground is at Wellesley Recreation Ground, named after Sir Arthur Wellesley, later to become the Duke of Wellington.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] There is a strong East Anglian rivalry with Gorleston.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Local football clubs are served by the Great Yarmouth and District League.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Great Yarmouth has a horse racecourse that features a chute allowing races of one mile (1.6 km) on the straight.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Speedway racing was staged before and after the Second World War.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The meetings were held at the greyhound stadium in Caister Road.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The post-war team was known as the Yarmouth Bloaters, after the smoked fish.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Banger and Stock car racing are also staged there.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The main Marina leisure centre, built in 1981, has a large swimming pool and conference facilities; it holds live entertainment, such as summer pantomime variety shows produced by local entertainers Hanton & Dean.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The centre is run by the Great Yarmouth Sport and Leisure Trust.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The Trust was set up in April 2006 to run the building as a charitable non-profit-making organisation.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] At the beginning of the 2008 summer season, the world's first Segway Grand Prix was opened at the Pleasure Beach gardens.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Local news and television programmes are provided by BBC East and ITV Anglia.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Television signals is received from the Tacolneston transmitter or from one of the two local relay transmitters (Great Yarmouth and Gorleston on Sea).
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The town's local radio stations are BBC Radio Norfolk on 95.1 FM, Heart East on 102.4 FM, Greatest Hits Radio Norfolk & North Suffolk (formerly The Beach) on 103.4 FM, and Harbour Radio, a community radio station that broadcasts from the town on 107.4 FM.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The *Great Yarmouth Mercury* is the town's weekly local newspaper, alongside the county-wide newspaper *Eastern Daily Press*.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The Wherry Lines link Norwich and Great Yarmouth railway station, with an hourly service operated by Greater Anglia; most services travel via Acle, with the remainder via Reedham.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The remaining Vauxhall station was renamed Great Yarmouth in 1989.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] It is the sole surviving station from a former total of seventeen within the borough limits.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The bus station in Great Yarmouth is the hub for local routes, located beneath Market Gates Shopping Centre.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Services are operated predominantly by First Eastern Counties.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The Excel X1 route, which links Norwich and Lowestoft, stops in the town.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Other local bus services link the suburban areas of Martham, Hemsby, Gorleston, Bradwell and Belton.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The River Yare cuts off Great Yarmouth from other areas of the borough, such as Gorleston and Southtown; as a result, the town's bridges became major transport links.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Originally, Haven Bridge was the only link over the river, but in the late 1980s, Breydon Bridge was built to take the A12 over Breydon Water, replacing the old railway bridge of Breydon Viaduct.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] In January 2020, construction began on a third river crossing, the Herring Bridge, which opened to traffic on 1 February 2024.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] All three are lifting bridges, which can be raised to allow river traffic to pass through; this can result in traffic tailbacks.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The phrase "the bridge was up" has become synonymous in the town with being late for appointments.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] A ferry running between the southern tip of Great Yarmouth and Gorleston provided a much shorter link between the factories on South Denes and the mostly residential areas of Gorleston.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] However, increased running costs and the decline of industrial activity led to its closure in the early 1990s.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Since 2006, the restored pleasure steamer the *Southern Belle* has offered regular river excursions from the town's Haven Bridge.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Built in 1925 for the Earl of Mount Edgcumbe, she is now owned by the Great Yarmouth and Gorleston Steam Packet Company Limited.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Construction work on the Great Yarmouth Outer Harbour, a deep-water harbour on the North Sea, began in June 2007 and was completed by 2009.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Originally, there was to be a roll-on/roll-off ferry link with Ĳmuiden, which failed to materialise.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] An initiative by Seamax Ferries to connect Great Yarmouth and Ijmuiden by ferry was due to start in 2008.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Nor did installation of two large cranes in 2009, since removed, save plans for a container terminal, which have also been scrapped.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] There has been a lifeboat at Great Yarmouth since at least 1802.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Early boats were privately operated until the RNLI took over in 1857.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] It has a lifeboat station at Riverside Road, Gorleston from where the Trent-class lifeboat *Samarbeta* and B class (inshore) lifeboat *Seahorse IV* run.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The anchorage off Yarmouth, known as *Yarmouth Roads*, was seen as one of the East Coast's best in the early 1800s.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Their fleets gathered and set sail during the Napoleonic wars.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Nowadays, the roadstead is more likely to be referred to as an anchorage.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The town is served by the A47 and the terminating A143.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Until 2017, the A12 from London terminated in Yarmouth; the route from Lowestoft was renumbered as the A47 by Highways England, as part of a wider road-improvement scheme.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Thereafter, the A12 has terminated in Lowestoft instead of at Vauxhall roundabout.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The relief road was built along the path of the old railway to carry the A12 onwards to Lowestoft and London.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Roundabouts, junctions and bridges often become gridlocked at rush hour.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Plans were advanced for a third river crossing in Great Yarmouth to link northern Gorleston with the South Denes and the Outer Harbour, avoiding the congested town centre.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] A public consultation took place in mid-2009 over four possible proposals, but plans were stalled by a lack of funding and closure of the container terminal.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] In 2016, additional funding of just over £1 million was pledged and a potential crossing proposal outlined for the crossing to link the A12 at Harfrey's Roundabout to South Denes.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The bridge project was approved in 2020 construction of the bascule bridge, to be named "Herring Bridge" began in January 2021, and was set to end in May 2023.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] During construction works, an unexploded German bomb from the Second World War was discovered and exploded during defusing attempts.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The bridge opened to road traffic on 1 February 2024.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] The North Denes Heliport, sited in the north of the town, is operated by CHC Helicopter.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] In 2011, the heliport's closure was announced, with operations moving to Norwich International Airport, but this has never occurred.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] An East of England Ambulance Service First Responder group has been set up for the Great Yarmouth area.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Made up of a group of volunteers within the community in which they live or work, they are trained to attend emergency 999 calls by the NHS Ambulance Service.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Great Yarmouth and Lowestoft Enterprise Zone was launched in April 2012.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Its sites include Beacon Park and South Denes in Great Yarmouth.
[src:great-yarmouth/great-yarmouth] Great Yarmouth has been twinned with Rambouillet, France since 1956.
